reasoning: 1. Circle of Competence: I’ve spent 60-plus years investing in businesses I understand—Coke, insurance, utilities. Selling auction‐based digital ads and running AI labs falls outside my wheelhouse. I’d be guessing at key revenue drivers, so I’ll step aside. 2. Moat: Alphabet likely enjoys a wide moat from network effects, search dominance and data scale. 3. Management: Sundar Pichai and team have proven capable capital allocators, but moonshots and side bets raise questions for a value investor who prizes predictable cash flows. 4. Financial Health: While I know Alphabet has a fortress balance sheet and consistent earnings, the provided data shows “insufficient fundamental data,” so I can’t verify debt levels or return on equity. 5. Valuation: No intrinsic-value or margin-of-safety figures are given—without them, price is what you pay and value is what you get remains an unanswered question. 6. Long-Term Prospects: AI and search will matter in 20 years, but regulatory risks and rapid tech shifts introduce uncertainty. 7. Portfolio Comparison: I’d rather own a wonderful consumer products business at a fair price than a fair tech business at an unknown price. Given my criteria and the missing data, I remain on the sidelines.
